<answer>Suppose \(\mathbf{v}= \begin{pmatrix} a \\ b \\ c \end{pmatrix} .\) Then, by Cramer's rule,
\begin{align*}
a &= \frac{336}{236}=-\frac{42}{29}, \quad b= \frac{182}{236}=\frac{91}{118}, \quad \text{and} \quad c= \frac{84}{236}=\frac{21}{59}.
\end{align*}
Therefore, the vector \(\mathbf{v} = \begin{pmatrix} -\frac{42}{29} \\ \frac{91}{118} \\ \frac{21}{59} \end{pmatrix}.\) </answer>

